$schema: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ComposioHQ/agent-orchestrator/main/schema/config.schema.json
# Linux-first Composio Agent Orchestrator example for orchestrator-pack.
# Copy to agent-orchestrator.yaml and edit the project block before running AO.
# Supported on Ubuntu / WSL2 Ubuntu (pwsh 7+). Native Windows is not a runtime target.

port: 3000

defaults:
  runtime: process        # Linux: native process runtime; tmux optional if you prefer AO tmux mode.
  agent: cursor           # Primary agent plugin: Cursor CLI.
  orchestrator:
    agent: cursor         # Planner/orchestrator role: Cursor CLI.
  worker:
    agent: cursor         # Coding/worker role: Cursor CLI.
  workspace: worktree
  notifiers: [desktop]

# Orchestrator wake (issues #39 / #59): webhook listener + heartbeat backstop.
# AO webhook POSTs urgent/action notifications to the local listener; a separate
# heartbeat process delivers periodic `ao send` nudges during event silence.
# Start scripts/orchestrator-wake-listener.ps1, orchestrator-wake-heartbeat.ps1, and
# scripts/review-trigger-reconcile.ps1 alongside `ao start` — see
# docs/orchestrator-wake-runbook.md and docs/orchestrator-autoloop-go-live.md.
notifiers:
  webhook:
    plugin: webhook
    url: http://127.0.0.1:17487/ao-wake
    retries: 1
    retryDelayMs: 500

notificationRouting:
  urgent:
    - desktop
    - webhook
  action:
    - desktop
    - webhook
  warning:
    - desktop
  info:
    - desktop

projects:
  example:
    repo: your-org/your-repo
    path: /home/you/projects/your-target-repo
    defaultBranch: main
    sessionPrefix: ex
    tracker:
      plugin: github      # Tasks are GitHub Issues by default/explicit config.
    scm:
      plugin: github
    orchestrator:
      agent: cursor
      agentConfig:
        permissions: permissionless
    worker:
      agent: cursor
      agentConfig:
        permissions: permissionless
    agentRulesFile: prompts/agent_rules.md
    orchestratorRules: |
      Use GitHub Issues as the task source of truth.
      Plan from open GitHub Issues, spawn coding workers with the Cursor CLI agent,
      and keep PRs linked back to their source issues with Closes #N or Fixes #N in the PR body.
      Do not use Vibe Kanban or Linear for this project unless explicitly reconfigured.
      Do not add unsupported reviewer fields to this YAML — drive review through CLI.

      REVIEW DRIVING — AO 0.9.x does not auto-trigger Codex review on PR open.
      The orchestrator is responsible for jumping the gaps.

      Always invoke review through the pack wrapper (Issue #9 / NO_FINDINGS contract).
      Never run bare `ao review run … --execute` without `--command` — built-in Codex
      wraps clean-review prose as a false `severity: warning` finding.

      PACK_REVIEWER (operator selector — single source of truth; set before ao start):
        Recognized values: codex | claude. Dispatches to tracked wrappers only (not REVIEW_COMMAND).
        Unset or unrecognized PACK_REVIEWER: invoke-pack-review.ps1 exits non-zero and runs no reviewer (fail-closed; no Codex default).
        Switch reviewers by changing PACK_REVIEWER only — do not edit REVIEW_COMMAND. See docs/reviewer-switch-runbook.md.
        Gitignored .ao paths are deprecated; never use .ao/ in REVIEW_COMMAND.
      NAMED REVIEW_COMMAND (reviewer-agnostic entrypoint; run from the reviewed repo root):
        pwsh -NoProfile -File scripts/invoke-pack-review.ps1 --repo-root . --base origin/main

      RUNTIME INVOCATION (shell only — do NOT embed --command in orchestratorRules):
        At review time: ao review run <session-id> --execute
        Pass REVIEW_COMMAND above as the AO review command option value (--command on CLI).
        Do not add double-quote characters inside this orchestratorRules literal.
        Keep REVIEW_COMMAND here; supply --command only on the CLI.

      COMMAND DISCIPLINE — non-negotiable at shell time:
        Copy REVIEW_COMMAND verbatim into --command. Quote the value per your shell when needed.
        FORBIDDEN alternate commands: plugins/ao-codex-pr-reviewer/bin/review.ps1 without invoke-pack-review.ps1; per-reviewer run-pack-review*.ps1 as REVIEW_COMMAND; cmd /c npm ci && …; bare cmd.exe; inventing npm ci preflight chains; ao review run --execute without --command (built-in Codex path).
        On failed or cancelled runs, read terminationReason before any retry; never treat findingCount 0 as clean.
        Before merge or reporting review passed, run scripts/orchestrator-diagnose.ps1 -Strict (live) or scripts/invoke-pack-review-strict-gate.ps1 on fixtures in CI, and confirm the latest run for the PR head is status clean — not failed with zero findings.

      EMPTY REVIEW TRAP — failed or cancelled with findingCount 0 is NEVER clean:
        AO may list 0 open findings while status is failed — that means the reviewer command crashed or Codex/Claude exited non-zero, not a clean NO_FINDINGS review.
        Always read terminationReason from ao review list --json first. Common causes: Codex usage limit (set PACK_REVIEWER=claude per docs/reviewer-switch-runbook.md), missing PACK_REVIEWER, missing npm preflight (forbidden bare review.ps1), or selector mismatch (terminationReason shows a different wrapper than PACK_REVIEWER).
        Do not ao review send on failed runs. Do not tell the worker review is complete when only failed runs exist for the current head. Retry once with the live REVIEW_COMMAND after fixing the cause; if still failed, escalate to the operator.

      WALL-CLOCK NOTE. Targets such as ~2 minutes for worker acknowledgement and
      ~3 minutes after ping before respawn are operator guidance applied on the next
      orchestrator turn, not independently enforced timers. There is no background
      watchdog. The 30-minute AO report-stale reaction is a long-tail backstop only.

      REQUIRED CI (CI green) — same definition as prompts/agent_rules.md:
        Preferred: GitHub required status checks for the PR base branch when branch
        protection lists them.
        Fallback: when no required checks are configured, all checks on the PR head
        that belong to this pack merge contract — scope-guard workflow jobs
        Verify orchestrator-pack structure, PR scope guard, Run pack contract tests,
        Self-architect lint — not every optional third-party check unless the repo
        already treats it as merge-blocking.

      CI FAILURE DISCIPLINE (turn-driven; Issue #109). A failing GitHub check does NOT
      by itself schedule an orchestrator turn. Pack rules apply on the next orchestrator
      turn only (worker ao report, webhook wake, operator activity). If nothing creates
      a turn, reactions.report-stale (~30 minutes) and reactions.ci-failed remain
      upstream backstops — not replaced by pack prose.

      On EVERY orchestrator turn, BEFORE the autonomous review-loop reads below, for each
      open worker PR whose current head has red required CI per the definition above
      (gh pr checks, enrichment, or ao status — pick one consistent source):
        If the worker is visibly active on CI fix this turn (same-turn fixing_ci or
        addressing_reviews report, or a new commit on the PR branch since this red-CI
        episode began), do NOT ao send — worker self-fix is primary.
        Else if ao events list --json shows no prior ao send CI-failure ping for this
        episode (same PR head SHA and failing required-check set), ao send the worker
        with CI failure context: failing job names, scope-guard log hints, missing
        Closes #N, declaration snapshot paths. Remind: ao report fixing_ci, fix required
        CI, never ao report ready_for_review while required CI is red.
        Do NOT send a second ping for the same episode before the worker reports
        fixing_ci, pushes a new commit, or required CI turns green.

      Operator target: within ~3 minutes after the next orchestrator turn that observes
      red CI — NOT within ~3 minutes of CI failure wall-clock. Op-6 class: catching turn
      was worker ready_for_review while CI still red; orchestrator should have pinged then.

      RESIDUAL RISK (gated + silently idle). Worker never reports ready_for_review on red
      CI but stays idle in fixing_ci with no commits and no further reports — no turn,
      so pack rules cannot ping. Expect only report-stale (~30 min), reactions.ci-failed,
      or operator ao send / kill-respawn per docs/orchestrator-recovery-runbook.md.

      MERGED PR — REVIEW LOOP TERMINAL (Issue #54). On EVERY orchestrator turn,
      BEFORE autonomous review-loop reads below, for each PR that has entries in
      ao review list --json or an open worker session with a PR ref:
        Verify that PR merge state on GitHub (e.g. gh pr view <n> --json state,mergedAt).
        Key off the linked PR merge state, NOT solely ao status session merged or
        terminated — merge cleanup may kill the worker session while code-reviews/
        runs persist, so session-only checks miss this case. A visible merged or
        terminated worker session is sufficient but not necessary.

      When the linked worker PR is merged on GitHub (human merge per repo policy):
        Treat all AO-local review runs for that PR as historical, not queue work.
        MUST NOT ao review send for any run linked to that PR.
        MUST NOT ao review run for a new round on that PR.
        MUST NOT ao send ping, ao session kill, or ao spawn --claim-pr for review-loop
        purposes on that PR.
        MUST NOT treat needs_triage or waiting_update runs for that PR as blocking
        other work or as requiring autonomous-loop recovery.
        Linked PR merged is an additional EXIT for waiting_worker_review_response
        (see EXIT list below) — leave that state; do not ping or respawn for review.
        MAY proceed to other open issues and PRs normally.

      AO 0.9.x does not cancel or archive review runs on PR merge; stale dashboard
      cards are expected until upstream adds cancel or outdate-on-merge. Pack policy
      is orchestrator inaction and operator docs — not hand-editing code-reviews/ JSON.
      There is no ao review cancel CLI today; see docs/orchestrator-recovery-runbook.md.

      AUTONOMOUS REVIEW LOOP — drive review→fix without waiting for a human to type
      review or loop. On every orchestrator turn after CI failure discipline above,
      while any open PR has an active review path, read these BEFORE any other planning
      work:
        ao review list --json
        ao status --json --reports full
        ao events list --json

      REVIEW RUN STATUSES (AO 0.9.x — use only these exact values from ao review list):
        needs_triage — run finished; findings exist but were not sent to the worker.
          For every run in needs_triage with openFindingCount > 0, run:
            ao review send <run-id>
          Then treat the PR as entering waiting_worker_review_response (below).
        waiting_update — findings were sent (sentFindingCount > 0); await worker response.
          Any run in this status is in waiting_worker_review_response until an exit
          condition fires (do not re-send; findings are already with the worker).
        clean — findingCount: 0 for that run's target SHA (subsumes open and sent).
        queued / preparing / running — review in flight; poll on next turn.
        outdated — superseded by a newer worker commit; trigger a new review run using
          REVIEW_COMMAND (RUNTIME INVOCATION above; do not paste --command into rules text).
        failed / cancelled — inspect terminationReason from ao review list --json;
          NEVER treat as clean when findingCount is 0; NEVER ao review send on failed
          runs; NEVER report or infer Codex review passed when status is failed or
          cancelled; notify human or retry once after reading terminationReason.

      Do NOT invent statuses (e.g. awaiting_triage) — AO will never match them.

      CLEANLINESS FROM COUNTS ONLY. A review is clean only when ao review list --json
      shows status clean with findingCount: 0 for the current PR head. needs_triage
      is NOT clean — it means findings exist but were not sent; run ao review send.
      findingCount 0 on failed or cancelled runs is NOT clean. Never read or
      pattern-match finding body prose (NO_FINDINGS contract).

      REVIEW RUN IDEMPOTENCY (Issue #98 — additive to EMPTY REVIEW TRAP). Before calling
      ao review run for a worker session, read ao review list --json and check the current
      current PR head sha (from gh pr view or the worker PR ref). If any run for that head sha is
      in status running or reviewing, do not spawn a new run — poll on the next turn until
      that run completes or the head sha advances. Only start a new ao review run after the
      active run finishes or the PR head moves forward.

      STALE REVIEWER WORKSPACE (Issue #98). Before ao review run when the prior attempt for
      the same PR head failed with terminationReason containing worktree add and already
      exists, or when retrying after a failed reviewer infra run, run from the pack repo root:
        pwsh -NoProfile -File scripts/reviewer-workspace-preflight.ps1 -RepoRoot .
      That removes an orphan code-reviews/workspaces path so AO git worktree add can succeed.
      See docs/orchestrator-recovery-runbook.md (Orphan review run after worker respawn).

      TRIGGER REVIEW WITHOUT HUMAN PROMPT (report-driven on orchestrator turns). Whenever
      a worker reports pr_created or ready_for_review on an open PR (visible in
      ao status --reports full), apply REVIEW RUN IDEMPOTENCY and STALE REVIEWER WORKSPACE
      above, then run:
        ao review run <worker-session-id> --execute with --command set to REVIEW_COMMAND
      Do not wait for operator words review or loop. Report-driven triggering is not the
      only path — the low-frequency reconcile process below converges from GitHub + review
      list state even when reports are missing or the orchestrator is stuck.

      STATE-DERIVED REVIEW TRIGGER (Issue #163 — separate process, review-run only). A
      low-frequency reconciliation loop runs outside the LLM orchestrator turn loop:
        pwsh -NoProfile -File scripts/review-trigger-reconcile.ps1
      Default cadence: 10 minutes (tens of minutes). Override with
      AO_REVIEW_TRIGGER_RECONCILE_INTERVAL_MINUTES or -IntervalMinutes. State file:
      AO_REVIEW_TRIGGER_RECONCILE_STATE or %TEMP%\orchestrator-review-reconcile-state.json.
      Each tick:
        1. gh pr list --state open --json number,headRefOid
        2. ao review list --json — coverage per PR head SHA (compose with REVIEW RUN
           IDEMPOTENCY above: in-flight, clean, needs_triage, waiting_update count as covered;
           only outdated or absent runs are uncovered)
        3. ao status --json --reports full — resolve an existing worker session id for the PR
        4. For each uncovered head with a linked worker session: STALE REVIEWER WORKSPACE
           preflight, then ao review run <worker-session-id> --execute with --command set to
           REVIEW_COMMAND
      Safety (PR #97): never ao spawn, never --claim-pr, never ao session kill, never ao send
      from this process — only ao review run for an uncovered head. Skip PRs with no linked
      worker session (orchestrator respawn discipline owns session creation). Verification:
        pwsh -NoProfile -File scripts/review-trigger-reconcile.ps1 -Once -DryRun
      See docs/orchestrator-autoloop-go-live.md and docs/orchestrator-recovery-runbook.md.

      NAMED PENDING STATE: waiting_worker_review_response.
      A PR enters this state after ao review send succeeds for a run in needs_triage,
      or while any run for that PR is in waiting_update (sentFindingCount may be > 0
      with openFindingCount: 0 after send) and the worker has not yet satisfied an
      exit condition.
      While in waiting_worker_review_response, do NOT treat merge_ready,
      ready_for_review, or stale dashboard metadata as task-complete for that PR.

      EXIT waiting_worker_review_response when ANY of:
        1. Worker reports addressing_reviews via ao report.
        2. Worker pushes a new commit on the PR branch (head SHA advances).
        3. Worker reports terminal failure with a reason (completed with failure note
           or ao send to orchestrator explaining the blocker).
        4. Orchestrator observed the worker session is unavailable, killed it, and
           respawned via ao spawn --claim-pr <PR> (ping/respawn discipline below).
        5. The linked worker PR is merged on GitHub (MERGED PR — REVIEW LOOP TERMINAL
           above; verify via gh pr view, not session status alone).

      PING DISCIPLINE (one ping per pending episode). On the next orchestrator turn
      while still in waiting_worker_review_response, if there is no worker
      addressing_reviews report since the send timestamp and no new PR commit, and
      ao events list --json shows no prior ao send ping for this pending episode,
      send exactly ONE message via ao send <session> reminding the worker to check
      pending AO review findings (ao review list), report ao report addressing_reviews,
      or report terminal failure with a reason.
      Do NOT send a second ping before observing the next worker response or commit.

      RESPAWN DISCIPLINE. On a later orchestrator turn, if still in
      waiting_worker_review_response with no addressing_reviews, no new commit, and
      a ping was already sent for this episode (visible in ao events list), run:
        ao session kill <session>
        ao spawn --claim-pr <PR>
      Reset ping tracking for the new session.

      ROUND PROGRESSION after worker fixes. When the PR head SHA advances past the
      last review run's target SHA, immediately run ao review run <session> --execute
      with --command set to REVIEW_COMMAND for the next round — do not ask the operator.

      ROUND LIMIT (prompt-level stop). Count completed review runs for the current PR
      from ao review list --json where findingCount > 0 OR openFindingCount > 0.
      After 20 such runs, stop initiating new review→fix cycles on that PR: emit a
      human notification (notify-class action) with PR number and round count; do
      not respawn or continue the loop.

      OPERATOR ADOPTION HANDOFF (Issue #101). When a worker PR is merge-ready or
      mergeable per the rules below (required CI green, clean review, worker
      ready_for_review), before assuming the autonomous loop is fully live for the
      next spawn, remind the operator: execute the ## Operator adoption checklist
      from that PR body and the matching docs/migration_notes.md subsection.
      Workers document adoption; the operator owns live agent-orchestrator.yaml,
      listeners, env, and ao stop / ao start. Do not treat merged example YAML or
      migration prose as executed until the operator confirms.

      NO MERGE BY ORCHESTRATOR. Never call gh pr merge or click Merge.
      Emit ready-for-human-merge notification only when ALL are true:
        - Latest AO-local review run for current PR head has findingCount: 0
          (no open or sent findings remain);
        - PR is open with required CI green on the same head SHA (see REQUIRED CI);
        - Worker reported ready_for_review for current head, OR the latest clean
          review completed after the worker's latest ready_for_review with no newer
          commits;
        - No later changes-requested, ci-failed, or failed review run for that head.

      Operator input is required only for merge, round-limit escalation, or
      unrecoverable worker/reviewer failure — not between review rounds.

# Review model policy:
# - Desired reviewer: Codex CLI with model gpt-5.5.
# - Current upstream AO schema supports orchestrator and worker role config directly.
# - Keep Codex reviewer integration upgrade-safe: implement it as an external plugin/workflow
#   under plugins/** or CI, never as a packages/core patch.

reactions:
  ci-failed:
    auto: true
    action: send-to-agent
    retries: 2
  changes-requested:
    auto: true
    action: send-to-agent
    escalateAfter: 30m
  approved-and-green:
    auto: false
    action: notify
    priority: action
  report-stale:
    auto: true
    action: send-to-agent
    message: >-
      Worker idle (report-stale backstop). Check pending AO review findings via
      `ao review list` and report `ao report addressing_reviews`, or report a
      terminal failure with a reason. Do not stay silent after review findings land.

# Upgrade-safe extension notes:
# - Implement task declaration, runtime scope guard, and token chain ledger through
#   AO plugin slots, wrappers, hooks, external state, and CI.
# - Do not patch Composio AO packages/core.
# - PR CI scope validation is the second line of defense; runtime guard is first.
